WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.470 --> 00:00:05.335
Prof: We last week
talked about the issue of women

00:00:05.335 --> 00:00:09.109
and early Christianity,
and I obviously didn't address

00:00:09.109 --> 00:00:13.199
all the different texts in early
Christianity that are relevant

00:00:13.199 --> 00:00:15.970
for your discussion last week on
women.

00:00:15.970 --> 00:00:18.590
We concentrated on the Pastoral
Epistles,

00:00:18.590 --> 00:00:21.941
I and II Timothy and Titus,
as representing one kind of

00:00:21.941 --> 00:00:25.106
early Christian way of handling
women in their early

00:00:25.106 --> 00:00:26.100
communities.
 

00:00:26.100 --> 00:00:29.405
Then we talked about the
Acts of Paul and Thecla

00:00:29.405 --> 00:00:32.159
as a very different kind of way
to do that.

00:00:32.159 --> 00:00:34.300
We're going to shift gears for
this week.

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:37.798
This week will also have
something of a theme about it,

00:00:37.798 --> 00:00:41.750
and the theme this week is the
interpretation of scripture.

00:00:41.750 --> 00:00:44.990
How do you interpret texts?
 

00:00:44.990 --> 00:00:49.331
I'm going to change gears from
what could be the basic method

00:00:49.331 --> 00:00:52.370
I've been using in the class all
along,

00:00:52.370 --> 00:00:54.130
which is the historical
critical method,

00:00:54.130 --> 00:00:56.119
which I've talked about
sometimes and explained what

00:00:56.119 --> 00:00:56.510
that is.
 

00:00:56.510 --> 00:00:59.068
We're going to talk about,
is that the only way for

00:00:59.068 --> 00:01:00.908
Christians to interpret
scripture?

00:01:00.908 --> 00:01:05.448
Today I get into that by
talking about the letter to the

00:01:05.448 --> 00:01:08.420
Hebrews as one very good
example,

00:01:08.420 --> 00:01:11.310
from the first period of
Christianity,

00:01:11.310 --> 00:01:14.349
of the interpretation of
scripture themselves.

00:01:14.349 --> 00:01:17.988
This is how Christians
themselves interpreted their

00:01:17.988 --> 00:01:20.390
scripture in the ancient world.
 

00:01:20.390 --> 00:01:23.078
This will be a lecture on
Hebrews to kind of talk about

00:01:23.078 --> 00:01:25.269
the content of the letter of the
Hebrews,

00:01:25.269 --> 00:01:29.543
but the main--it's also used to
shift our gears away from a

00:01:29.543 --> 00:01:33.669
purely historical critical
analysis of scripture and show

00:01:33.669 --> 00:01:36.690
how ancient people did it
themselves.

00:01:36.690 --> 00:01:39.435
Then next class period,
on Wednesday,

00:01:39.435 --> 00:01:43.324
we'll talk about medieval
exegesis, late ancient and

00:01:43.324 --> 00:01:46.373
medieval
exegesis--interpretations of the

00:01:46.373 --> 00:01:47.290
Bible.
 

00:01:47.290 --> 00:01:50.358
Now I got the feeling last
week, when I was lecturing about

00:01:50.358 --> 00:01:52.370
the Acts of Paul and
Thecla,

00:01:52.370 --> 00:01:56.059
that there were quite a few of
you in attendance who perhaps

00:01:56.059 --> 00:01:59.811
