00:02:24.318 --> 00:02:27.544
Print it out if you need to and
bring it to class because I will

00:02:27.544 --> 00:02:30.205
be talking about that,
and your reading for Wednesday

00:02:30.205 --> 00:02:31.688
is not part of the Bible.
 

00:02:31.688 --> 00:02:34.990
It's from a very,
very, very important book,

00:02:34.990 --> 00:02:38.137
one chapter,
which you probably should all

00:02:38.137 --> 00:02:40.210
rush right out and buy.
 

00:02:40.210 --> 00:02:42.979
It's so brilliant and so
wonderfully written.

00:02:42.979 --> 00:02:45.318
I published the book last
summer, it's called,

00:02:45.318 --> 00:02:48.331
Pedagogy of the Bible,
and I'll set that in a little

00:02:48.331 --> 00:02:49.318
bit of context.
 

00:02:49.318 --> 00:02:51.408
What that is,
is I actually went around and

00:02:51.408 --> 00:02:54.543
studied ten different seminaries
and divinity schools around the

00:02:54.543 --> 00:02:56.562
country,
all Protestant seminaries,

00:02:56.562 --> 00:02:57.620
but very different.
 

00:02:57.620 --> 00:02:58.877
Some of them were very
conservative,

00:02:58.877 --> 00:03:00.530
with conservative denominations
in churches;

00:03:00.530 --> 00:03:02.250
some were very liberal and
progressive.

00:03:02.250 --> 00:03:05.020
What I did was I interviewed
both professors and students,

00:03:05.020 --> 00:03:07.508
about fifty professors and
about fifty students,

00:03:07.508 --> 00:03:11.454
most of whom were planning to
be ordained into the ministry of

00:03:11.454 --> 00:03:12.229
some sort.
 

00:03:12.229 --> 00:03:15.400
Most of these students are
people who are studying theology

00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:18.843
and scripture precisely because
they will end up preaching about

00:03:18.843 --> 00:03:21.960
this and working in churches for
most of their cases.

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:26.003
I asked them,
how are you taught to study the

00:03:26.003 --> 00:03:26.740
Bible?
 

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:31.129
I reported that material back
in the first chapter of that

00:03:31.129 --> 00:03:33.979
book, Pedagogy of the
Bible.

00:03:33.979 --> 00:03:35.360
I basically have said,
here is what I've found,

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:37.000
and the main thing I found was
that,

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:39.444
almost all these people,
although they were really being

00:03:39.444 --> 00:03:41.561
taught--
they were supposed to be taught

00:03:41.561 --> 00:03:44.634
how to read this text as a
theological document for modern

00:03:44.634 --> 00:03:45.389
Christians.
 

00:03:45.389 --> 00:03:47.751
They actually are pretty much
only being taught historical

00:03:47.751 --> 00:03:49.508
criticism,
what the text meant in the

00:03:49.508 --> 00:03:51.910
ancient world,
just like I am teaching you in

00:03:51.910 --> 00:03:52.568
this class.
 

00:03:52.568 --> 00:03:54.968
Now I think that this makes
perfect for me to use the

00:03:54.968 --> 00:03:57.551
historical critical method to
teach you because this is a

00:03:57.551 --> 00:03:58.660
secular environment.
 

00:03:58.660 --> 00:04:00.318
I don't assume that you're
Christian,

00:04:00.318 --> 00:04:02.060
I don't assume that you're
religious at all,

00:04:02.060 --> 00:04:04.724
I don't assume that you're
coming into this class with the

00:04:04.724 --> 00:04:07.532
interest of studying the New
Testament as a document for your

00:04:07.532 --> 00:04:08.000
faith.
 

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.290
For some of you that's clearly
the case, but that's not the

00:04:10.290 --> 00:04:12.383
structure of this course,
as I explained from the very

00:04:12.383 --> 00:04:13.568
beginning of the semester.
 

00:04:13.568 --> 00:04:16.925
I use the historical method as
the way to introduce you to this

00:04:16.925 --> 00:04:20.120
material simply because it's an
easy way to introduce modern

00:04:20.120 --> 00:04:23.098
students to a historical
document as we approach it that

00:04:23.098 --> 00:04:23.639
way.
 

00:04:23.639 --> 00:04:26.023
I've also said several times in
the class, that's not the only

00:04:26.023 --> 00:04:27.040
way to read these texts.
 

00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:29.199
What we're going to talk about
this week is,

00:04:29.199 --> 00:04:31.310
what are other ways to read
these texts?

00:04:31.310 --> 00:04:32.810
That's what I did in that book.
 

00:04:32.810 --> 00:04:35.740
Then in the second chapter of
that book was introducing

00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:39.245
theories of interpretation,
some of which I'll do today,

00:04:39.245 --> 00:04:42.060
textual theory and
interpretation theory.

00:04:42.060 --> 00:04:46.353
The third chapter of the book
was pre-modern interpretation of

00:04:46.353 --> 00:04:50.720
scripture, which is the chapter
that I'm asking you to read.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:54.303
That's where I take certain key
figures among the church

00:04:54.303 --> 00:04:56.930
fathers,
such as Origen,

00:04:56.930 --> 00:05:02.410
Augustine, the Venerable Bede
in England,

00:05:02.410 --> 00:05:06.250
Bernard of Clairvaux in the
Middle Ages,

00:05:06.250 --> 00:05:07.709
and Thomas Aquinas.
 

00:05:07.709 --> 00:05:11.786
I show how those people read
the Bible before the invention

00:05:11.786 --> 00:05:15.088
of the modern method of
historical criticism.

00:05:15.088 --> 00:05:18.459
I don't just do that because I
think it's interesting.

00:05:18.459 --> 00:05:21.461
I'm putting it in that book
because I'm trying to advocate

00:05:21.461 --> 00:05:24.569
in that book how schools should
change their curriculum,

00:05:24.569 --> 00:05:27.057
how Christian theological
schools should change their

00:05:27.057 --> 00:05:29.591
curriculum so that it will
better teach people who are

00:05:29.591 --> 00:05:31.839
going to be ministers how to
interpret scripture

00:05:31.839 --> 00:05:34.040
theologically and not just
historically.

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:36.459
The third chapter is pre-modern
stuff.

00:05:36.459 --> 00:05:38.389
The fourth chapter of that
book, which you won't read,

00:05:38.389 --> 00:05:41.017
unless you rush right out and
order it from Amazon.com and

00:05:41.017 --> 00:05:43.488
read it on your own time,
is on theological

00:05:43.488 --> 00:05:44.600
interpretation.
 

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:47.110
What does it mean to talk about
a theological interpretation of

00:05:47.110 --> 00:05:49.459
text that's not the same as a
historical interpretation?

00:05:49.459 --> 00:05:51.399
I explained that,
I give examples of it,

00:05:51.399 --> 00:05:53.089
and then in the last chapter of
the book,

00:05:53.089 --> 00:05:55.728
the fifth chapter,
I lay out what I would propose

00:05:55.728 --> 00:05:58.641
as a new curriculum for
theological education and what

00:05:58.641 --> 00:06:01.060
the role of scripture should be
in that.

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:03.723
I talk about that precisely
because I want you to know that

00:06:03.723 --> 00:06:06.019
when you're reading that chapter
for Wednesday,

00:06:06.019 --> 00:06:08.069
and I do want you to read it
ahead of time,

